<div id="main-content">


			
				<article id="post-1599" class="post-1599 project type-project status-publish has-post-thumbnail hentry project_category-a-changing-society et_pb_post">

				
					<div class="entry-content">
					<div id="et-boc" class="et-boc">
			
			<div class="et_builder_inner_content et_pb_gutters3">
				<div class="et_pb_section et_pb_section_0 et_pb_fullwidth_section et_section_regular">
				
				
				
				
					<section class="et_pb_module et_pb_fullwidth_header et_pb_fullwidth_header_0 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_text_align_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_fullwidth_header_container center">
					<div class="header-content-container center">
					<div class="header-content">
						
						<h1 class="et_pb_module_header">Race, Housing, and Poverty</h1>
						<span class="et_pb_fullwidth_header_subhead">A Changing Society</span>
						<div class="et_pb_header_content_wrapper"></div>
						
					</div>
				</div>
					
				</div>
				<div class="et_pb_fullwidth_header_overlay"></div>
				<div class="et_pb_fullwidth_header_scroll"></div>
			</section>
				
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_section --><div class="et_pb_section et_pb_section_1 et_section_regular">
				
				
				
				
					<div class="et_pb_row et_pb_row_0">
				<div class="et_pb_column et_pb_column_4_4 et_pb_column_0    et_pb_css_mix_blend_mode_passthrough et-last-child">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_module et_pb_text et_pb_text_0 et_pb_bg_layout_light  et_pb_text_align_left">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_text_inner">
					<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="#alltopics">View all topics for &#8220;A Changing Society&#8221; &gt;</a></p>
				</div>
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_text --><div class="et_pb_module et_pb_slider et_pb_slider_0 et_pb_slider_fullwidth_off">
				<div class="et_pb_slides">
					<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_0 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center et-pb-active-slide">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">1 of 10</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><p style="text-align: left;">Chicago&#8217;s ethnic and racial diversity helped make it the international city Daley celebrated. From World War I (1914-1918) onward, this diversity grew richer and more complex as hundreds of thousands of black Americans from the South moved to Chicago in search of better economic opportunities and freedom from the Jim Crow restrictions against their civil rights. In Chicago they found jobs, access to schooling, and some political representation.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">But black Chicagoans also found widespread discrimination. &#8220;Redlining&#8221;  and other practices shunted blacks into small, overcrowded ghettos on the city&#8217;s south and west sides. Black residents believed they did not enjoy the services and opportunities available to white Chicagoans. This de facto segregation, along with the related issues of poverty, proved difficult to resolve.</p>
<div id="attachment_989" style="width: 610px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0194_2204_4.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-989" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0194_2204_4-1024x783.jpg" alt="Reverend Martin Luther King, Jr. at a Chicago Freedom Movement rally in Soldier Field," width="600" height="459" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0194_2204_4-1024x783.jpg 1024w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0194_2204_4-300x229.jpg 300w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0194_2204_4-1080x826.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0194_2204_4.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Reverend Martin Luther King, Jr. at a Chicago Freedom Movement rally in Soldier Field, July 10, 1966. CULR_04_0194_2204_004</p></div></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
				</div> <!-- .et_pb_container -->
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide -->
			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_1 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">2 of 10</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><p style="text-align: left;">James Compton, a civil rights activist and the former president of the Chicago Urban League, discusses race relations and politics in Chicago while Daley was mayor. Click on image to play video.</p>

<!-- iframe plugin v.4.3 wordpress.org/plugins/iframe/ -->
<iframe width="420" height="315" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/Ecc1q2mO8So" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" 0="allowfullscreen" scrolling="yes" class="iframe-class"></iframe>

<p style="text-align: right;"><em>Video: James Compton, Civic Leader and Civil Rights Activist, interview excerpt, August 27, 2010</em></p></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
				</div> <!-- .et_pb_container -->
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide -->
			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_2 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">3 of 10</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><p style="text-align: left;">In 1966, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and his colleagues came to Chicago to work with other likeminded activists to improve the conditions of urban slums, end housing discrimination, and expand access to public schooling.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id="attachment_986" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/BHC_0001_0014_001DE.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-986 size-large" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/BHC_0001_0014_001DE-1024x664.jpg" alt="Inside pages of Southern Christian Leadership Conference Newsletter, vol. III, no. 1, January-February, 1966. BHC_0001_0014_003_001de" width="1024" height="664" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/BHC_0001_0014_001DE-1024x664.jpg 1024w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/BHC_0001_0014_001DE-300x194.jpg 300w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/BHC_0001_0014_001DE-1080x700.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/BHC_0001_0014_001DE.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Inside pages of Southern Christian Leadership Conference Newsletter, vol. III, no. 1, January-February, 1966. BHC_0001_0014_003_001de</p></div></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
				</div> <!-- .et_pb_container -->
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide -->
			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_3 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">4 of 10</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><p style="text-align: left;">Andrew Young was a member of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference. He accompanied Martin Luther King Jr. on his 1966 visit to Chicago. Click on image to play video.</p>

<!-- iframe plugin v.4.3 wordpress.org/plugins/iframe/ -->
<iframe width="420" height="315" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/MwwZg9jz14w" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" 0="allowfullscreen" scrolling="yes" class="iframe-class"></iframe>

<p style="text-align: right;">Video: <em>Andrew Young, Mayor of Atlanta, interview excerpt, October 16, 2014</em></p></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
				</div> <!-- .et_pb_container -->
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide -->
			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_4 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">5 of 10</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><blockquote>
<p style="text-align: left;">I was at the mayor&#8217;s office when Dr. King came in. What surprised me the most was – first, the room was filled with ministers, elected officials, his aides, and department heads, and people were talking – but when Dr. King came in, the silence he brought into that room and the command. And he was not a tall man. I was shocked, but I remember the quietness. As soon as he entered the room, it became quiet. And then he sat right across from my dad. They discussed the problems in the city that he came to address. And he said, &#8220;Dr. King, we&#8217;re willing to work with you, we will work this out.&#8221; And they came up with a plan, my dad and him. They announced it.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>John Daley, son of Richard J. Daley, interview excerpt, May 9, 2007</em></p>
</blockquote>
<div id="attachment_987" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0192_2179A_001.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-987 size-medium" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0192_2179A_001-300x199.jpg" alt="Reverend Martin Luther King, Jr. greeting people from the back of a truck, ca. 1966. CULR_04_0192_2179.a_001" width="300" height="199" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0192_2179A_001-300x199.jpg 300w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0192_2179A_001-1024x680.jpg 1024w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0192_2179A_001-1080x717.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/CULR_04_0192_2179A_001.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Reverend Martin Luther King, Jr. greeting people from the back of a truck, ca. 1966. CULR_04_0192_2179.a_001</p></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote>
<p style="text-align: left;">It was a tough period in the ‘60s with the open housing marches in the middle 1960s. You had Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. marching on the southwest side, and the mayor was largely responsible for helping to develop the agreement that provided for open housing.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>James O&#8217;Connor, Executive at Commonwealth Edison, interview excerpt, July 22, 2014</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em> </em></p></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
				</div> <!-- .et_pb_container -->
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide -->
			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_5 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">6 of 10</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><p style="text-align: left;">Some steps the mayor took to address poverty and housing shortages were controversial, particularly the decision to use federal money to build high-rise public housing.</p>
<div id="attachment_1001" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_017B.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-1001 size-medium" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_017B-300x237.jpg" alt="Two men inspect wiring in an apartment" width="300" height="237" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_017B-300x237.jpg 300w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_017B-1024x808.jpg 1024w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_017B-1080x852.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_017B.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Two men inspect wiring in an apartment at 1611 S. Ridgeway in the Lawndale neighborhood, 1971. RJD_04_01_0033_0002_017B</p></div>
<blockquote>
<p style="text-align: left;">And so I think his inspiration initially on public housing might have been right, to get people into new, in those days, new dwellings, even high-rise public housing. But also it was to make sure that the black and white problem was going to be contained within certain areas. As that public housing disintegrated, you could tell this was not the answer.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>Richard J. Durbin, United States Senator, interview excerpt, September 8, 2014</em></p>
</blockquote></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
				</div> <!-- .et_pb_container -->
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide -->
			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_6 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">7 of 10</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><p style="text-align: left;">Michael Daley explains why the city adopted high-rise housing. Click on image to play video.</p>

<!-- iframe plugin v.4.3 wordpress.org/plugins/iframe/ -->
<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/EOFUoK9MA2Y" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" 0="allowfullscreen" scrolling="yes" class="iframe-class"></iframe>

<p style="text-align: right;">Video: <em>Michael Daley, son of Richard J. Daley, interview excerpt, July 21, 2006</em></p></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
				</div> <!-- .et_pb_container -->
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide -->
			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_7 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">8 of 10</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><div id="attachment_1002" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_018C.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-1002 size-medium" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_018C-300x266.jpg" alt="Architect's rendering of proposed public housing at 1555-60 N. Sandburg Terrace" width="300" height="266" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_018C-300x266.jpg 300w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_018C-1024x907.jpg 1024w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_018C-1080x956.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0033_0002_018C.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">An architect&#8217;s rendering of proposed public housing at 1555-60 N. Sandburg Terrace, 1971. Photo: Bill Engdahl, Hedrich-Blessing. RJD_04_01_0033_0002_018c</p></div>
<blockquote>
<p style="text-align: left;"> I think that he was against high-rise housing all of the time. He didn&#8217;t think that the high-rise housing was a good idea.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>Newton Minow, Chair of Federal Communications Commission 1961-1963, interview excerpt, October 2, 2003</em></p>
<p style="text-align: right;">
</blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote>
<p style="text-align: left;">The ones that bothered him were the high-rise public housing. He said, &#8220;Father, we had this problem and we went to the experts to ask what to do. And they told us to build these high-rise things. It was the biggest mistake I ever made. We would just pile a slum on a slum. And they were just terrible.&#8221; But that bothered him tremendously. But he said, &#8220;We didn&#8217;t know any better.&#8221; And most of them are gone now.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>Father Gilbert Graham, Daley Family Friend, interview excerpt, November 17, 2003</em></p>
</blockquote></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
				</div> <!-- .et_pb_container -->
				
			</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide -->
			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_8 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">9 of 10</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><p style="text-align: left;">Daley and others speak at the groundbreaking for Lake Grove Village apartments in 1971. Click on image to play video.</p>

<!-- iframe plugin v.4.3 wordpress.org/plugins/iframe/ -->
<iframe width="420" height="315" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/v85L2V49gUA" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" 0="allowfullscreen" scrolling="yes" class="iframe-class"></iframe>

<p style="text-align: right;">Video: <em>Excerpt from &#8220;Event,&#8221; RJD_04_02_0000_0000_299a</em></p></div>
							
						</div> <!-- .et_pb_slide_description -->
					</div>
